Erythrocyte microRNAs: a tiny magic bullet with great potential for sickle cell 
disease therapy.

Verma HK(#)(1), Ratre YK(#)(2), Bhaskar LVKS(3), Colombatti R(4).

Author information:
(1)Institute of Endocrinology and Oncology CNR, 83031, Naples, Italy. 
henu.verma@yahoo.com.
(2)Department of Biotechnology, Guru Ghasidas Vishwavidyalaya, Bilaspur, 495009, 
India.
(3)Department of Zoology, Guru Ghasidas Vishwavidyalaya, Bilaspur, 495009, 
India.
(4)Clinic of Pediatric Hematology Oncology, Department of Woman's and Child's 
Health, University of Padova, Via Giustiniani 3, 35128, Padova, Italy.
(#)Contributed equally

Sickle cell disease (SCD) is a severe hereditary blood disorder caused by a 
mutation of the beta-globin gene, which results in a substantial reduction in 
life expectancy. Many studies are focused on various novel therapeutic 
strategies that include re-activation of the γ-globin gene. Among them, 
expression therapy caused by the fetal hemoglobin (HbF) at a later age is highly 
successful. The induction of HbF is one of the dominant genetic modulators of 
the hematological and clinical characteristics of SCD. In fact, HbF compensates 
for the abnormal beta chain and has an ameliorant effect on clinical 
complications. Erythropoiesis is a multi-step process that involves the 
proliferation and differentiation of a small population of hematopoietic stem 
cells and is affected by several factors, including signaling pathways, 
transcription factors, and small non-coding RNAs (miRNAs). miRNAs play a 
regulatory role through complex networks that control several epigenetic 
mechanisms as well as the post-transcriptional regulation of multiple genes. In 
this review, we briefly describe the current understanding of interactions 
between miRNAs, their molecular targets, and their regulatory effects in HbF 
induction in SCD.

